---
import Docs from '../../layouts/Docs.astro';
---
<Docs title="Disposables" description="One cancellation primitive for everything." eyebrow="Concept">
  <p>
    Every allocation — a ticker handle, a MobX reaction, an event listener, a Pixi
    resource — implements <code>Disposable</code> and is owned by a parent that tears it down.
  </p>
  <pre><code>{`export interface Disposable {
  dispose(): void;
}`}</code></pre>
  <p>
    Phases dispose their tickers on <code>exit</code>. Scenes dispose their presenters
    on teardown. <code>DisposableBag</code> collects children so the parent doesn't have
    to remember handles individually.
  </p>

  <h2>Rule of thumb</h2>
  <p>
    If you write <code>const x = something.on(...)</code> or
    <code>const x = ticker.schedule(...)</code>, the return value has a <code>dispose</code>
    and the parent is responsible for calling it.
  </p>

  <h2>Why</h2>
  <p>
    A slot runs for hours. Tiny leaks — a callback here, a listener there — compound.
    Resource-leak bugs are usually invisible for the first week and lethal by the second.
    A consistent disposal contract turns "did anyone clean this up?" into "yes, its
    parent did, in <code>dispose()</code>."
  </p>

  <h2>Idempotence</h2>
  <p>
    <code>dispose</code> is safe to call twice. Implementations no-op after the first call.
    This lets parents dispose aggressively without tracking "already disposed" flags.
  </p>
</Docs>
